.TH POSISH 1 "March 2026" "posish 0.1.3+" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
posish \- POSIX-first shell with documented extensions
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B posish
[\-abCefhimnuvx] [+\-abCefhimnuvx] [\-o
.IR option ]
... [+
.B o
.IR option ]
... [\-s]
[\-c
.IR command
[
.IR command_name
[
.IR argument
...
]]]
[
.IR command_file
[
.IR argument
...
]]
.br
.B posish
.B \-\-version
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B posish
is a C11 shell implementation that aims for POSIX behavior first and keeps its
extensions documented.  It supports interactive use, script execution,
job control, startup files, and a small prompt-expansion language.
.PP
This manual describes current behavior.  It does not promise compatibility
beyond what is explicitly documented here.
.SH INVOCATION
If
.B \-\-version
is given as the first argument,
.B posish
prints its version and exits.
.PP
If
.B \-c
is used, the next operand is taken as the command string.  If another operand
follows, it becomes
.BR $0 ;
later operands become the positional parameters.
.PP
If a command file operand is present,
.B posish
executes that file in non-interactive mode.
.PP
With no
.B \-c
and no command file,
.B posish
reads commands from standard input.  It enters interactive mode by default only
when standard input is a terminal, unless interactivity is forced with
.BR \-i .
.PP
A shell whose
.B argv[0]
starts with
.B \-
is treated as a login shell.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-\-version
Print the shell version and exit.
.TP
.BI \-c " command"
Execute
.I command
instead of reading commands from a file or standard input.
.TP
.B \-i
Force interactive mode.
.TP
.B \-s
Read commands from standard input.
.TP
.BI \-o " option"
.TP
.BI +o " option"
Enable or disable a named shell option.
.TP
.BR \-a ", " +a
Enable or disable
.BR allexport .
.TP
.BR \-b ", " +b
Enable or disable
.BR notify .
.TP
.BR \-C ", " +C
Enable or disable
.BR noclobber .
.TP
.BR \-e ", " +e
Enable or disable
.BR errexit .
.TP
.BR \-f ", " +f
Enable or disable
.BR noglob .
.TP
.BR \-h ", " +h
Enable or disable
.BR hashondef .
.TP
.BR \-i ", " +i
Enable or disable
.BR interactive .
.TP
.BR \-m ", " +m
Enable or disable
.BR monitor .
.TP
.BR \-n ", " +n
Enable or disable
.BR noexec .
.TP
.BR \-u ", " +u
Enable or disable
.BR nounset .
.TP
.BR \-v ", " +v
Enable or disable
.BR verbose .
.TP
.BR \-x ", " +x
Enable or disable
.BR xtrace .
.PP
Named options currently include:
.BR allexport ,
.BR notify ,
.BR noclobber ,
.BR errexit ,
.BR noglob ,
.BR hashondef ,
.BR interactive ,
.BR monitor ,
.BR noexec ,
.BR nounset ,
.BR verbose ,
.BR xtrace ,
.BR pipefail ,
and
.BR ignoreeof .
.SH STARTUP FILES
.B posish
currently loads only user-scoped startup files.
No system-wide startup files such as
.I /etc/profile
are used.
.PP
Startup order is:
.TP
interactive shell
.B ENV
(if set), then
.IR ~/.posishrc
(if
.B HOME
is set)
.TP
login shell
.IR ~/.posish_profile
(if
.B HOME
is set)
.TP
interactive login shell
.IR ~/.posish_profile ,
then
.BR ENV ,
then
.IR ~/.posishrc
.TP
non-interactive
.B \-c
or command file execution
No startup files are loaded.
.TP
non-interactive login shell
.IR ~/.posish_profile
only
.PP
If
.B HOME
is unset or empty,
.I ~/.posish_profile
and
.I ~/.posishrc
are skipped.
.PP
Missing startup files are silent.  Existing but unreadable startup files produce
a diagnostic.
.SH PROMPTS
In interactive shells,
.B posish
initializes prompt variables only when they are unset:
.TP
.B PS1
defaults to
.BR "\ew \e$ " .
.TP
.B PS2
defaults to
.BR "> " .
.PP
Prompt rendering performs simple parameter expansion, then prompt escape
expansion.  Command substitution and arithmetic expansion are not performed in
prompts.
.PP
Supported prompt parameter forms are:
.BR $name ,
.BR ${name} ,
.BR $? ,
.BR $$ ,
.BR $! ,
.BR $# ,
and
.BR $0 .
Unsupported parameter operators are left literal.
.PP
Supported prompt escapes are:
.TP
.B \e\e
literal backslash
.TP
.B \ea
bell
.TP
.B \ee
escape byte
.TP
.B \en
newline
.TP
.B \er
carriage return
.TP
.B \eu
user name
.TP
.B \eh
short host name
.TP
.B \eH
full host name
.TP
.B \es
shell name
.TP
.B \ew
current working directory, shortened with
.B ~
when under
.BR HOME
.TP
.B \eW
basename of
.BR \ew
.TP
.B \ed
date in
.B "%a %b %d"
format
.TP
.B \et
time in 24-hour
.B HH:MM:SS
format
.TP
.B \eT
time in 12-hour
.B HH:MM:SS
format
.TP
.B \eA
time in 24-hour
.B HH:MM
format
.TP
.B \e$
.B #
for effective uid 0, otherwise
.BR $
.TP
.B \e#
interactive top-level command counter
.TP
.B \ej
active tracked job count
.PP
Unknown prompt escapes are rendered as the escaped character.
.SH SIMPLE COMMANDS AND BUILTINS
.B posish
supports the usual shell command forms: simple commands, pipelines, async
lists, subshells, and brace groups.
.PP
Special builtins include:
.BR : ,
.BR . ,
.BR break ,
.BR continue ,
.BR eval ,
.BR exec ,
.BR exit ,
.BR export ,
.BR readonly ,
.BR return ,
.BR set ,
.BR shift ,
.BR times ,
.BR trap ,
and
.BR unset .
.PP
Regular builtins include:
.BR cd ,
.BR pwd ,
.BR true ,
.BR false ,
.BR echo ,
.BR printf ,
.BR test ,
.BR [ ,
.BR kill ,
.BR wait ,
.BR fg ,
.BR bg ,
.BR umask ,
.BR alias ,
.BR unalias ,
.BR getopts ,
.BR hash ,
.BR jobs ,
and
.BR type .
.PP
For command discovery,
.BR pwd ,
.BR echo ,
and
.BR printf
are reported in substitutive style by
.BR "command -v"
and
.BR "command -V" .
For example,
.B command -V echo
reports that
.B echo
is a substitutive built-in for the external
.IR echo (1)
path that would otherwise be found.
.PP
The current
.B echo
implementation prints its operands separated by single spaces and always adds a
trailing newline.  It does not currently interpret
.B \-n
or backslash escapes as options.
.SH EXPANSIONS
.B posish
supports the standard shell expansion pipeline used by its parser and
executor, including parameter expansion, command substitution, arithmetic
expansion, field splitting, and pathname expansion where applicable.
.PP
Prompt expansion is separate from normal command-word expansion and is limited
to the forms described in
.BR PROMPTS .
.SH REDIRECTIONS
The shell supports input, output, append, heredoc, and descriptor-duplication
redirections in the executor's current POSIX test contract.
.PP
Redirection errors such as missing operands, ambiguous expansions, or invalid
descriptor duplication operands produce diagnostics and cause the command to
fail.
.SH JOB CONTROL
When monitor mode is enabled, stopped and background jobs are tracked by job
and process group rather than by a single pid.
.PP
Jobspecs support:
.BR % ,
.BR %+ ,
.BR %% ,
.BR %- ,
.BI % number ,
.BI % string ,
and
.BI %? string .
.PP
.BR fg ,
.BR bg ,
.BR wait ,
and
.BR kill
operate on whole jobs.  For pipelines, job status follows the rightmost command
in the pipeline.
.SH EXIT STATUS
A simple command normally exits with the status returned by the executed
builtin, function, or utility.
.PP
Syntax errors generally produce status 2.  Signal termination is reported using
the shell's encoded status internally and is relayed as a real terminating
signal on final process exit where appropriate.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
Important shell-related variables include:
.TP
.B ENV
Interactive startup hook, executed before
.IR ~/.posishrc .
.TP
.B HOME
Used to resolve
.I ~/.posish_profile
and
.IR ~/.posishrc ,
and for prompt
.B \ew
home shortening.
.TP
.BR IFS
Initialized to the default <space><tab><newline> baseline.
.TP
.BR OPTIND
Initialized to
.BR 1 .
.TP
.BR OPTARG
Starts unset.
.TP
.BR PATH ,
.BR PWD ,
.BR OLDPWD
Imported from the parent environment unless normal shell execution updates
them.
.TP
.BR PS1 ,
.BR PS2
Interactive prompts, initialized only when unset.
.SH CONFORMANCE AND EXTENSIONS
.B posish
targets POSIX shell behavior first.
.PP
Documented extensions currently include:
- prompt escapes in
.B PS1
and
.BR PS2
- user startup files
.I ~/.posish_profile
and
.I ~/.posishrc
- additional named shell options such as
.B pipefail
and
.BR ignoreeof
.PP
The test strategy is POSIX-first and uses imported yash POSIX tests as a major
validation source.
.SH BUGS
The shell is still under active development.
.PP
Not every user-facing behavior is guaranteed to match other shells outside the
documented contract above.
